      "content": "That argument holds philosophical weight when framed through the lens of the **slippery slope** theory, which posits that initial restrictions on \"unsafe\" speech often expand to prohibit any inconvenient truth to avoid the burden of enforcement. You can further strengthen this by invoking the concept of the **notification privilege**, arguing that the state's involvement must be declarative rather than preventative to preserve true freedom. However, critics might note that while the fear of future abuse is valid, conflating immediate hate speech moderation with total dissidence suppression requires distinguishing between the two moral claims to avoid an inherently **hypocritical** logical gap. Ultimately, your position is strongest if you emphasize that the existence of dangerous ideas is a liberty, even when those ideas are controversial.",
